is that the proxy class needs to be loaded on the client side. While `Javassist` server creates proxy `CtClass`, it doesn't define it, and `ObjectImporter.createProxy` will load the original fixture from the test classpath instead of the proxy. I could export a class that acts as both proxy and fixture. It could have a constructor that takes `ObjectImporter` and an index for method calls. But, I'd need a way to determine the method index dynamically.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring method ordering**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I could exploit the ordering of `ExportedObject` methods by exporting a Java class with public methods. The aim is to ensure stability across JDK versions, though I’m not sure if that's feasible. I could use a test fixture proxy with a static `methodId` computed via reflection with `Arrays.asList(RemoteService.class.getMethods())`. The rules say not to use reflection unless the public API requires it. In this case, it seems natural given that `AppletServer's` RMI protocol relies on method IDs based on `getMethods`. However, the test’s own `getMethods` might not apply to the active class.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_XoROREP2r0ZRrsnPqP5fcTZ6|fc_03466d1b8f067e720169f50bb936bc819fb89d9fff2cb445a3", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge10/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/javassist/javassist/3.12.0.GA/main/extracted/javassist/tools/rmi/RemoteRef.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 417, "output": 1072, "cacheRead": 28672, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30161, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777666984318, "responseId": "resp_03466d1b8f067e720169f50ba8c5f8819fb7f7b70d05cdef01"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_XoROREP2r0ZRrsnPqP5fcTZ6|fc_03466d1b8f067e720169f50bb936bc819fb89d9fff2